for six years as part of her gender-affirming care. She has no significant medical history and takes no other regular medications. She has no family history of breast cancer. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate breast cancer screening recommendation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Annual mammogram starting immediately","No screening required as risk is minimal","Biennial mammogram from age 50-74","Screening only if symptoms develop","Annual clinical breast examination only"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBreast cancer screening recommendations for transgender individuals should be based on individual risk factors and anatomy. For transgender women who have been on gender-affirming hormone therapy for five or more years, current evidence supports following similar screening guidelines to cisgender women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial mammogram from age 50-74\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for transgender women who have been on oestrogen therapy for five or more years, as this population has a similar risk profile to cisgender women. The duration of hormone exposure is a key factor in determining breast cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual mammogram starting immediately\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive and is not supported by current evidence. There is no indication for more frequent screening than the general population in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo screening required\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as transgender women on long-term hormone therapy do have a measurable risk of breast cancer, albeit lower than cisgender women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening only if symptoms develop\u003C/strong\u003E represents an inadequate approach to preventive care, as the purpose of screening is to detect cancer before symptoms develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual clinical breast examination only\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient as a screening strategy. Clinical examination should complement, not replace, mammographic screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that transgender men who have not had chest masculinisation surgery should follow the same screening guidelines as cisgender women. After chest masculinisation surgery, screening recommendations depend on the amount of remaining breast tissue and should be individualised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transgender women who have taken gender-affirming hormones for 5+ years should undergo breast cancer screening every 2 years from age 50-74.","Transgender men who have not had chest surgery should follow the same breast cancer screening guidelines as cisgender women.","After chest masculinisation surgery, screening recommendations depend on the amount of remaining breast tissue."],"references":["Blok CJM de, Wiepjes CM, Nota NM, Engelen K van, Adank MA, Dreijerink KMA, et al. Breast cancer risk in transgender people receiving hormone treatment: nationwide cohort study in the Netherlands. BMJ [Internet]. 2019 May 14;365. Available from: https://www.bmj.com/content/365/bmj.l1652","\u200cInformation for trans and gender diverse people [Internet]. Breast Screen. 2024 [cited 2024 Nov 10]. Available from: https://www.breastscreen.nsw.gov.au/community-support/trans-and-gender-diverse-people/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45784"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45784"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-11T07:28:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-11T07:30:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"item